ustry and key sectors of the medical profession came to be allies against pharmaceutical reform. It details the political strategies they have used to influence public opinion, shape legislative reform, and define the regulatory environment of prescription drugs. Untangling the complex relationships between drug companies, physicians, and academic researchers, the book provides essential historical context for understanding how corporate interests came to dominate American health care policy after World War II.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 29. Mai 2023) 0aDrugsxResearchzUnited StatesxHistoryy20th century. 0aPharmaceutical industryzUnited StatesxHistoryy20th century. 7aMEDICAL / History.2bisacsh  aaddiction.  aamerican healthcare.  aantibiotics.  adangers of drugs.  adiscussion books.  adoctors and drugs.  adrug addiction.  adrug company history.  adrug corruption.  adrug regulation.  adrug safety.  adrug use in america.  adrug use.  adrugs.  aeasy to read.  aengaging.  agreat for reluctant readers.  ahealthcare after world war ii.  ahealthcare in united states.  ahistorical.  ainformative books.  ainteresting books.  amedical relationships.  amedicine and science.  apharmaceutical reform.  apharmaceuticals.  aphysicians and drug companies.  aprescription drugs.08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertUniversity of California Press Backlist Package 2000-2013z97831106904220 cprintz978052027114240uhttps://doi.org/10.1525/978052095242340uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780520952423423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9780520952423/original  a978-3-11-069042-2  University of California Press Backlist Package 2000-2013c2000d2013  aEBA_FAO  aEBA_UCA_YUP  aGBV-deGruyter-alles  aZDB-23-UCY